s%20and%20gives%20you%20more%20value%20as%20a%20team%20member.%3C%2Fp%3E%3Ch2%20data-toc-id%3D%5C%22c2ebfbd3-fb34-4292-9dcf-21d465d3955b%5C%22%3EDon't%20play%20nice%3C%2Fh2%3E%3Cp%3ELee%20said%20many%20of%20us%20have%20been%20%3Ca%20href%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Fwww.businessinsider.com%2Fnice-workplace-culture-might-be-red-flag-nyu-professor-2023-7%5C%22%20target%3D%5C%22_blank%5C%22%3Econditioned%20to%20play%20nice%20at%20work%3C%2Fa%3E%2C%20and%20that%20can%20result%20in%20people%20holding%20back%20insight%20or%20providing%20overly%20harsh%20criticism.%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cp%3EInstead%2C%20you%20should%20treat%20feedback%20as%20a%20way%20to%20help%20others%2C%20Lee%20said.%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cp%3ETo%20do%20so%2C%20%3Ca%20href%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Fwww.businessinsider.com%2F5-tips-for-giving-constructive-feedback-in-the-office-2012-11%5C%22%20target%3D%5C%22_blank%5C%22%3Eyou%20should%20provide%20constructive%20feedback%3C%2Fa%3E%20early%20and%20act%20as%20a%20sounding%20board%20for%20others.%20Lee%20said%20you%20should%20voice%20unpopular%20opinions%20and%20respectfully%20challenge%20leaders%20when%20you%20feel%20passionately%20about%20a%20topic.%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cp%3ELee%20said%20early%20in%20his%20career%2C%20he%20preferred%20getting%20feedback%20from%20nice%20people%20because%20of%20the%20%26quot%3Bpsychological%20safety%20and%20confidence%20boost%26quot%3B%20it%20gave%20him.%20Now%2C%20he%20turns%20to%20people%20who%20offer%20genuine%20feedback.%20He%20said%20it's%20sometimes%20uncomfortable%20%E2%80%94%20but%20much%20more%20useful.%3C%2Fp%3E%3Ch2%20data-toc-id%3D%5C%227276d954-9c33-4785-a266-2f72777bd857%5C%22%3EConnect%20the%20dots%20for%20others%3C%2Fh2%3E%3Cp%3ELee%20said%20you%20should%20offer%20insight%20to%20coworkers%20even%20when%20they%20don't%20know%20they're%20looking%20for%20it.%20That%20means%20actively%20thinking%20about%20what%20other%20teams%20are%20working%20on%2C%20instead%20of%20solely%20focusing%20on%20your%20own%20tasks%2C%20Lee%20said.%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cp%3EFor%20examp